AdminComments: Changed to xuj (jenn1240) from mal (sout2708) on 26 May 2016 based on feedback from H. Hammarstr√∂m: "The people Bhanu studied natively speak a variety of Kurumba-Jennu [xuj]"; previously matched to language "mal" based on KK note: "lat/long coordinates for society place it in Central Kerala state, much closer to lat/long for mal than for xuj (which is in neighbouring Tamil Nadu state). I couldn't access the sources, though

Note that Terashima (1980), the main source of cultural data for this group, says further research is needed to confirm whether Bambote speak language of a neighbouring group, or their own language. Both the Bambote and their neighbours say the group speaks a distinct language, "Kimbote." Rebecca Grollemund said this society should NOT be matched to iso "tap"; she said "Bambote is a pygmy language related to D20 languages"
I think this should be the "Ouahigouya" dialect of Mossi (mos), though there is no such dialect in Glottolog.
Note, previously lenc1244, but glottocode is considered a "bookkeeping" code (because extinct?), so chose Lencan-Honduras instead (note that point is in Honduras)

reclassified another society from [mal] to [xuj] on 26 May 2016; as a result, matched this society to the glottolog language [mala1464] (which we are more certain of), replacing match to dialect [cent1998] (less certain)
Note, previously nzu and teke1279, but glottocode teke1279 is considered "bookkeeping", and SIL says nzu and ebo are said to be neighbouring dialects. Therefore, switched to ebo.
Changed to Kamviri (xvi) from pbu based on village in which one of two main sources spent most of his time (Kamdesh)

Note, previously this language was associated with xd758, and with both Binford and EA "Punan"ÔÜù societies. This xd_id now refers only to the Binford "Punan"ÔÜù society, with the EA "Punan"ÔÜù society linked to xd758 and language iso "pna"ÔÜù (3 Mar 2016). In May 2016 received this further comment from H. Hammarstr√∂m: "The references here reference different hunting and gathering populations of Borneo, not all of which speak the [same] language" "[...] if you have to put one [language] for all of these then a better match is Penan-Western [pne] because e.g Urquhart 1951 is on Penan Gang and Penan Lusong and Brosius is on Penan Gang. Both Penan Gang and Penan Lusong speak varieties of Penan-Western [pne]."
Note, previously tasm1247, but languages difficult to assign with certainty, so chose another western tasmanian language not considered a "bookkeeping" language by glottolog
Note, three Cahuilla Dialects (Mountain, Pass, Desert) are recognized by some, but Glottolog does not list any dialects
